    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - SHIFT CONTROL LINKAGE WITH MANUAL TRANSMISSION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsection id="s13004" svcsectype="prodspec" division="truck" formnum="CTS-5230" date="03/31/1996">
        <title>SHIFT CONTROL LINKAGE WITH MANUAL TRANSMISSION</title>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>9800</truckmodel>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The transmission shift control linkage used on the 9800 model vehicles is illustrated in
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300401">Figure 1</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1300401" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300401" filename="../figg13/G1300401.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 1. Exploded View of Transmission Shift Control Language</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. TRANSMISSION CONTROL HOUSING</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. TRANSMISSION CONTROL HOUSING BOOT</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. SHIFT LEVER SEAL</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. GEAR SHIFT KNOB</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. GEAR SHIFT LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>6. LEVER SEAL RETAINER</callout1>
                            <callout1>7. BEARING SEAL RETAINER</callout1>
                            <callout1>8. SELF-ALIGNING BEARING</callout1>
                            <callout1>9. CONTROL ROD GUIDE</callout1>
                            <callout1>10. SHIFT LEVER BELL</callout1>
                            <callout1>11. SPRING</callout1>
                            <callout1>12. REMOTE CONTROL HOUSING</callout1>
                            <callout1>13. PIVOT ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>14. SELECTION LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>15. REMOTE CONTROL - OUTER SHIFT LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>16. CONTROL ROD CLAMPS</callout1>
                            <callout1>17. TRANSMISSION CONTROL ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>18. CONTROL ROD BALL</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The shift control system consists of the following:</para>
                    <seqlist style="arabic">
                        <item>
                            <para>The shift lever and its mounting parts located in the cab (
                                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300402">Figure 2</hotlnk>).
                            </para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>The remote control tower assembly located on the top of the transmission (
                                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300403">Figure 3</hotlnk>).
                            </para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>The control rod assembly which connects the shift lever (in the cab) to the
                                transmission remote control housing. Components of the control rod assembly are shown in
                                <hotlnk xrefid="f1300404">Figure 4</hotlnk>.
                            </para>
                        </item>
                    </seqlist>
                    <figure id="f1300402" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300402" filename="../figg13/G1300402.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 2. Shift Lever</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f1300403" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300403" filename="../figg13/G1300403.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 3. Control Tower Assembly</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. CONTROL ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. OUTER SHIFT LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. PIVOT ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. REMOTE CONTROL HOUSING</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="f1300404" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300404" filename="../figg13/G1300404.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 4. Control Rod Assembly</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. CONTROL ROD BALL</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. CONTROL ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. CLAMP BOLT</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. SELECTION LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. CLAMP BAR (2)</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>Control rod assemblies are provided in different lengths to accommodate various
                        engine/transmission combinations. The effective lengths (Dimension A,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300405">Figure 5</hotlnk>) for various combinations are listed in
                        <hotlnk document="s13004_7.xml" xrefid="hl1300401">SPECIFICATIONS
                            <xref refid="hl1300401"/>
                        </hotlnk>
                        .
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1300405" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300405" filename="../figg13/G1300405.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 5. Effective Lengths</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>A. APPROXIMATE TRUE LENGTH</callout1>
                            <callout1>1. TRANSMISSION CONTROL ROD</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>If replacement of the control rod is required, refer to the parts catalog for the correct
                        replacement parts. Assemble the parts to provide the specified length (Dimension A, (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300405">Figure 5</hotlnk>) listed in
                        <hotlnk document="s13004_7.xml" xrefid="hl1300401">SPECIFICATIONS
                            <xref refid="hl1300401"/>
                        </hotlnk>
                        , for the engine and transmission in the vehicle being serviced.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>Refer to
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300406">Figure 6</hotlnk>for Items in parentheses.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1300406" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300406" filename="../figg13/G1300406.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6. Upper End of Control Rod</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. SHIFT LEVER SOCKET</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. SPRING</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. CONTROL ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. SUPPORT BRACKET</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. ROD GUIDE</callout1>
                            <callout1>6. BEARING</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>With the cab lowered in the driving position, the front (upper) end of the control rod
                        connects to the shift lever (in the cab) as shown in
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300406">Figure 6</hotlnk>. The front end of the control rod is supported by
                        the control rod bearing (Item 6) and the control rod ball is engaged into the shift lever socket
                        (Item 1).
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>When the cab is raised (tilted), the shift lever socket disengages from the control ball and
                        the control rod bearing (connected to the shift lever housing) disengages from the control rod.
                        The control rod support bracket (Item 4) keeps the control rod from falling out of position.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>When the cab is lowered, the control rod guide (Item 5) guides the end of the control into
                        alignment with the control rod bearing. The spring (Item 2) holds the shift lever in position to
                        permit the shift lever socket to engage with the control rod ball.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>Refer to
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300407">Figure 7</hotlnk>for Items in parentheses.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1300407" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300407" filename="../figg13/G1300407.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 7. Lower End of Control Rod</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>A. 93&#176;15` - 93&#176;45` WITH INTERNATIONAL 9-SPD AND SPICER 10-SPD 90 DEGREES
                                ALL OTHER TRANSMISSIONS
                            </callout1>
                            <callout1>1. CONTROL ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. REMOTE CONTROL HOUSING</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. PIVOT ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. SELECTION LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. OUTER SHIFT LEVER</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The rear (lower) end of the control rod is connected to the transmission remote control
                        housing as shown in
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300407">Figure 7</hotlnk>. The selection lever (Item 4), which is the rear
                        portion of the control rod assembly, is connected to the remote control outer shift lever (Item
                        5) and to the lower end of the pivot rod assembly (Item 3). Swivel bearings are used at these
                        locations to provide flexibility and ease of operation.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The remote control housing for International 9-speed and Spicer 10-speed transmissions is
                        shown in
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300408">Figure 8</hotlnk>.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1300408" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300408" filename="../figg13/G1300408.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 8. Remote Control Housing</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. REMOTE CONTROL HOUSING</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. PIVOT ROD ASSEMBLY TURNBUCKLE</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. LOCK NUTS</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. PIVOT ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>The length of the pivot rod is adjustable to accommodate various engine/transmission
                        combinations. The effective lengths for various combinations are listed in
                        <hotlnk document="s13004_7.xml" xrefid="hl1300401">SPECIFICATIONS
                            <xref refid="hl1300401"/>
                        </hotlnk>
                        .
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>If replacement of the pivot rod is required, refer to the parts catalog for the correct
                        replacement parts. Assemble the parts to provide the specified length (
                        <hotlnk document="s13004_7.xml" xrefid="hl1300401">SPECIFICATIONS
                            <xref refid="hl1300401"/>
                        </hotlnk>
                        ,
                        <hotlnk document="s13004_9.xml" xrefid="f1300421">Figure 21</hotlnk>, Dimension F).
                    </para>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <para>Fuller and Spicer units have the pivot rod assembly attached directly to the remote control
                        housing rather than to a pivot rod bracket (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1300409">Figure 9</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1300409" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1300409" filename="../figg13/G1300409.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                        <caption>Figure 9. Pivot Rod Assembly</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. PIVOT ROD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. REMOTE CONTROL OUTER SHIFT LEVER</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. REMOTE CONTROL HOUSING</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. PIVOT ROD CONNECTION</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
